{
  "answer": "**In *The Wanderer* (from *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11), the phrase \"Hwaer cwom mearg, hwaer cwom mago\" appears in the famous *ubi sunt* (\"where are they?\") lament near the poem's end (ll. 92b–93).**[^1]\n\nImmediately following it—still within the same line—is **\"Hwaer cwom maththumgyfa?\"** (literally \"Where [has] come treasure-giver?\"; trans. \"Where [has] the treasure-giver gone?\"), evoking the image of a vanished lord or treasure-dispenser from the lost heroic age.[^2]\n\nThis launches the sequence lamenting the transience of earthly glory: treasure-giver → feast-seats (*symbla gesetu*) → hall-joys (*seledreamas*) → bright cup (*beorht bune*) → mailed warrior (*byrnwiga*) → princely majesty (*þeodnes þrym*).[^3]\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), transliteration, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/#p-2ecb4b).\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), transliteration (`ll. 92b–93`): [\"Hwær cwom mearg? Hwær cwom mago? Hwær cwom maþþumgyfa?\"](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/#p-2ecb4b); translation: [\"'Where has the horse gone? Where has the warrior gone? Where the treasure-giver?\"](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), transliteration (`ll. 94–95`): [\"Hwaer cwom symbla gesetu? Hwaer sindon seledreamas? / Eala beorht bune! Eala byrnwiga! / Eala þeodnes þrym!\"](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/#p-2ecb4b); cf. translation [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).",
